3 63\nGoldfield Con... 5 51-16 4 15-16 3 5146\nTfreene Cananea. 7 7 67% 6%\nGreene Gold-Sil.. a\nMcKiniey Dar... 11-16 3% 11-16 11-16\nMitchell Mining. 1% on 1% 1 1%\nNevada Con..... Sie 7% 8 8%\nNevada Smeit., 1 1 1 1\nNevada Utah.. 278 25% 2% 213-16\nNipissing 6% 9% 6% 6%\nSilver Queen.... 7% s 13-16 13-16\nTramp Con....... 163% 16% 16%\nTri ullicn...... 28 23\n2\nUnited Copper... 45% 4\u00a2\nChicago Subway 16% tort\nManh. Trans..... VR A\nStandarq Oil..... 432 482\nLBBB 4 oer sitaniasiens $1,083,401,900\nDeposits 1,026,047.800\nCirculation 5,001,800\nLegal tenders... 62,608,600\nTS SE 198,558,800\nARBRE. ovis\u00bb Rasasien 261,\nf ale\nRequired oe 256,611,950\nBRACTIEE yore simi amen us 4,655,450\n655\nEx. U. 8S. Deposits 13,027,350\nThe snirnhie af the hanke ia\ns da BH\nBEES\n208.8,\nFEET\nBREE SE\nThe surplus of the banks is $4,655,450,\nagainst 034,400 last year, -and $10,211,\n400 two vears ago.\n*Increase.\ngrade rails at present prices. The As\nclines o1 the week have been heavy.\nsome cases almost sensational.\n\nAmalgamated Copper dropped 5 poinis\nSmelting nearly 10 points, Atchison\nnearly 7, Baltimore and Ohio over 3, Ca\nnadian Pacific 4 Mts, St. Paul 21,\nGreat Northern 3, uisiville and Nash\nville 5, Missouri, Kansas, and Texas 5,\nReading 314, Union Pacific 4%, Steel com\nmon 2, and preferred neariy 4. These\ncomparisons are with the closing prices\nof a week ago today, and not with the\nhigh of the week.\n\nThe strongest possible hope of a rally\ncomes in the oversold condition of the\nmarket, and the fact that the shorts\nwould turn quickly if the news was\nmore favorahie.\n\n\nRailroad earnings have not been en\ntirely satisfactory. Some roads, like\nthe Rock Island and Atchison, have\ndone well, but the chief trouble seems\nto lle in the increase In operating ex\npenses due to high wages and increased\nost of operating.\nThe net loss for the wees is shown in\nthe following table, siving the closing\nprices of last week and the cl\norices of todav:\nat,\nOct. 5.\nAmalgamated Copper..... hog\nAnaconda: ..coivciviniinivins 363,\nSmelting common.......... 8i3g\nAtchison preferred......... 89\nBaltimore Ohlo..........\nhesapeake Ohlo........ 323,\nCanadian Pacifie............ 162\nChi., Milwaukee St. P..117\nDelaware Hudson...... 156\nGreat Northern pfd........ 128\nIllinois Central.............. 1\nLouisville Nashville..... 104\nMo., Kansas RAS... x\nNorthern Paecific............\nPennsylvania wea 118%\nReading ...\u00ab...i:.i0.. Awrninr 3\nSouthern Pacifle............ %1\nBnion: Paelfie....... 00 lhl\n8 Bee). i. cusses rian cnnnn\n134%,\n99\n0\n237%\n11. 8. .Sieel.arsferr\nS83. 834\naa\n\n2\nCEES\nE38\n52\na\nNew York Stocks\n\nBANK STATEMENT.\nThe Declines.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, SUNDAY, OCTOBER 13, 1907.\nFISH ON SCENE\nREADY TG FIGHT\nFOR. C. CONTROL\nWill Line Up Against Harri\nman and Harahan\nWednesday.\nHarahan Claims He Has\nEnough Votes to Win\nRattle.\nCHICAGO, Oct, 12.\u2014Stuyvesant Fish\ncame to Chicago tonight to open his\nficht on Bdward H. Harriman and Pres.\nident James T. Harahan for the control\nof the Illinois Centra! \u00bbiilway Com\npany. At the same tim\u00a2 ame the an\nnouncement that Mr. J riman would\nreacn Chicago Monday, 4 that A. G.\nHackstaff, Eastern fleld irsnal for the\n\u2018Harriman side of the coil oversy, would\nreach the city by tomorrow.\nThe first actual hostilities on the\nground opened when Mr. Fisa reached\nthe Annex at 7 o'clock. After a hurried\ndinner. he had a number of advisers\nwith him, and the actual task of pre\nparing for ednesday's battle, when\nthe stockholders of the road meet to\nelect four directors, was under way long\nbefore midnight.\nWould Save Own Scalp.\nAt first it seemed that tne former\npresident would take to the warpath\nafter his enemies. As the time drew\non, however, the war paint faded. It\nbecame more evident that he was in a\nstruggle to save hile own scalp. There\ncame strong evidences from the Harri\nman-Harahan camp that Fisa would\nhave his hands full to retain a place\non the board of directors. Mr. Fish did\nnot himeelf have any particular rebut\nting evidence to offer to the apparent\nadvantage of his hated rivals,\nPresident Harahan, at his office,\nsmoked and looked pleased with the\nsituation. He sald that he was. He\nleft the irapression that his side of the\nfight would have a majoritv of the\n950,400 votes Wednesday in the big fight.\nHe showed more contentment with the\nsituation than did Mr. Fish.\nHas Enough Strength.\n\u201cHow many proxies have your peo\nple?\u201d he was asked. o\n\u201cEnough,\u201d he said.\n\u201cWill the use of tne Union Pacific's\nstock be enjoined by Mr. Fish?\u201d\nThere came some talk that a deal\nmight be made wllereby Mr. Fish might\nretain his place on the board. It brought\nno contirmatory statements from any\nsource. The four directors who retire\nare: Stuyvesant Fish, A. G. Hackstaff,\nH. Harriman, and John Jacob Astor.\nr. Hackstaff is filling the unexpired\nterm of the late John C. Welling.\nMr. Fish brought with lum S(uyvesant\nFieh, jr., and P. R. Bome Isler. Thea\nFish punch was checked with the bag\ngage. It's owner was nervous and un\nwilling to take the community at large\ninto his confidence as to his plans. Here\nfs how the conversation with him ran\nalong:\n\n\n\u201cWill you have a majoriiv of the\nproxies in Wednesday's meeting?\u201d\n\u201cAsk Harahan; he knows all about\n\u201cWho is Bom~> Isler, who came with\nyou?\"\n\u201cHe is a stockholder\u2014and a gentle\nman.\u201d\nThe phraseoiogy might have 'ndicated\nthat some stocrxholders were rot.\nInterest of Stockholders\n\u201cWhat is your object in coming to\nChicago and entering this fight if it og~\nrears that you are honcless!y beaten\nir advance?\"\n\u201cI am here to attend thie stockhold\nors\u2019 meeting in the interest of the\n\u2018stockholders. What things are to de\nelop at the meeting are 8f the future\nand I am not going to speak of th\nfuture.\u201d\nFINANCIAL GOSSIP\nFailures during the third-quarter of\n1907 are very materially larger than they\nwere for the same quarter of 1906. The\nflgures of liabilities compare $28,\n099,309 for 1907, with $8,420,454 for 1906.\nTrade failures are materiaily less, com\nparing $13,000,000 to $10,000,000. Septem\nber vas a bad month for both the man\nufaecturing and the retail end of the\nbursin-ss world. The total commercial\nfer th- third quarter were near\n2400000, 28 compared with a little\ner M000, 000 a vear ago.\nTune slump in sugar last week was en\ntirely unexpected, as this stock has\npractically been taken out of the list\nof speculative securities. A loss of\na share on Friday denoted long selling.\nThe shock of confidence through the\ndisclosures in the various corporations\ntnat have been held to the legal light,\nis considered by Henry Clews Co. as\none of the causes of liquidation.\nThe United States is not alone in the\nthrces of financial liquidation. All Eu\nrope is in a bad way, while the public\nlooks on and spends $109.000 for ball\nFamees\nTEST OF ITS WORK\nThe test of the work of a Legislature,\nwhether it is good or bad, is how if\nwears on the people. Does anybody sup\npose that any of the laws enacted b\nthe last Legislature increasing tne ef\nficiency of the several schools of the\nState, including the public schools, will\nbe repealed by any future Legisiature?\nJas tne Legislature passed any laws\nnaterially affecting the welfare of peo\nole of the State that any future Legisla\nture dare repeal, unless they are re\npealed to make them more up to date\nand to conform with present-day condi\ntions, just as that much-zbused back\ntax law of Governor Johnston was re\npealed to make way for another more\nstringent, and more effective, looking\nto up-to-date methods of achieving the\nsame ends the back-tax law was enacted\nto accomplisa?\nWhen people in years to come be\nn to sum up the the present Leg\nture has accomplished, and compare\nits work with past Legislatures, it\nwould not he surprising to see the bal\nance of good and ive legislation on\nthe credit side offghe Iegislature of\nyi\nNEW YORK MONEY\n\nNEW YORK, Oct, 12.\u2014Money on call\nwas quoted nominally at 5 per cent to\nday. Rates during the week have rang\u00e9d\nbetween and 2% per cent, averaging 5.\nThe whole market was active through\nout the week, with a hardening tend\nency. Rates were yery firm. On Mon\nday loans were made ar and 4%; Xyges\nday, at 6 and 5 per cent; Wednesday, 6\nand 38; Thupsday, 6 and 4 and Friday,\nat 4% wud 4%.\nTime money was firm thpaughout the\nweek. Demand was not pressing, but\nofferings were meager, and borrowers\ncontinued to show a preference for loans\nof January maturity. Rates on ninety\nday loans were advanced to 6% per\ncent. Offerings at 7 per cent for this\nclass of loans did not meet with muca\nresponse. Rates for four to six month\nmaturities were generally 6 per cent.\nMercantile paper continued duil and\nunchanged throughout the week. A lit\ntle buying was reported from the\nsmaller country banks, but the volume\nof business was small. Rates 7 per\ncent for four to six months\u2019 bille receiv\nable, and prime single names; 7% per\ncent for others.\nSterling was firm, with demand bills\n10 points higher at 4.86%.\nMISCELLANEOUS BONDS\nTEW YORK, Ot. 12.\u2014S8tock exchange\nTEW YORK, Ont. 12.\u2014Stock exchange\nbond transactions:\nN. Y. city 3 i temp. ctfs...... 1053\nN.X. hy 1917, temp. 05 1 0h\nImperi Pte FB eanhesrenes\nJuaperial Jagancs M iS mein 31%\nmpe apanese 4's...... 0\nAmerican Tobacco Co. $'s R%\nAmerican Tobacco Co. 4 62\nCentral Georgia eon. 192%;\nBe: Le Pines 30\nE A i rig. 4's.. B63:\nP. col. 4's. 60%\nBistiiiers Security Co. 5's Wh\nl.ake Shore 4's, 1331...... 8%\nNe XC la 8.3. .oennsee ng\nNorthern Pacific 4's.......... I\nNorthern Pacific 3's............. an\nPennsylvania, 10 a. sss sss sssnsssanss 85s\nPennsylvani:. 3 11's, 1s 1915........... 837%\nROMAINE: 4 8. v3 ar cn nsnsinoss